The knowledge graph synthesis engine operates in continuous cycles, pairing nodes for cross-pollination based on embedding cosine similarity. Candidate pairs are filtered through a similarity window: a floor threshold of 0.5 ensures minimum semantic overlap, while a ceiling of 0.92 rejects pairs that are too similar to produce novel insights. Selected pairs are sent to the voicing subsystem, which generates a JSON response containing a single-sentence insight synthesized from both parents. The output undergoes multiple quality gates: JSON validity, sentence completeness (must end with punctuation), word count bounds (10-25 words), novelty ratio (at least 4 words not in either parent), and stutter detection for repeated phrases. Successful syntheses become new nodes linked to both parents via weighted edges. Node salience decays by 2% every 10 cycles to prevent runaway weight accumulation, while breakthrough nodes receive a permanent weight floor that exempts them from decay. The engine respects partition boundaries — nodes in different partitions never pair unless an explicit bridge exists between their partition groups.